      = Sergey Ivanov\n| image               = Sergei Ivanov 2016 Referee.jpg\n| image_size          = \n| fullname            = Sergey Sergeyevich Ivanov\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1984|06|5|df=yes}}\n| birth_place         = \n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| otheroccupation     = \n| years1 = 2008\u20132009 | league1 = [[Russian Second Division|PFL]] | role1 = [[Assistant referee (association football)|Assistant referee]]\n| years2 = 2009\u20132013 | league2 = [[Russian Professional Football League|PFL]] | role2 = [[Referee (association football)|Referee]]\n| years3 = 2011\u20132015 | league3 = [[Russian Football National League|FNL]] | role3 = [[Referee (association football)|Referee]]\n| years4 = 2012\u2013     | league4 = [[Russian Premier League|RFPL]] | role4 = [[Referee (association football)|Referee]]\n}}\n\n'''Sergey Sergeyevich Ivanov''' ({{lang-ru|\u0421\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0435\u0439 \u0421\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0435\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0418\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432}}; born 5 June 1984) is a [[Russia]]n [[association football|football]] referee. He lives in [[Rostov-on-Don]].\n\nHe has been a [[FIFA]] referee since 2014.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[FIFA]]|url=https://www.fifa.com/development/education-and-technical/referees/association=rus/index.html|title=Russia - Referees - Men|accessdate=16 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://rfpl.org/rfpl/arbitr/arbitr_3361.html Profile by Russian Premier League]\n* [http://footballfacts.ru/referees/116224-ivanov-sergej-sergeevich Profile by footballfacts.ru]\n\n{{UEFA First Category Referees}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ivanov, Sergey}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Russian football referees]]\n\n{{Russia-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "update links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sergey_Ivanov_(referee)"}
{"title_page": "Franco-Spanish War (1635\u20131659)", "text_new": "{{short description|Franco-Spanish conflict of 1635-1659}}\n{{Other uses|Franco-Spanish War (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict   = Franco\u2013Spanish War\n|image      = HeimBattleRocroy.jpg\n|image_size = 250px\n|caption    = [[Battle of Rocroi|Rocroi]]; a French victory that ended Spanish [[Tercio]] dominance of the European battlefield  \n|date       = 19 May 1635 \u2013 7 November 1659 <br />({{age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=05|day1=19|year1=1635|month2=11|day2=07|year2=1659}})\n|place      = Northern, Eastern and Southern [[France]], Northern [[Spain]], the [[Spanish Netherlands]], [[Italy]], [[Atlantic Ocean]], [[Mediterranean Sea]]\n|territory  = [[Artois]], [[Roussillon]] and [[Perpignan]] annexed by France\n|result     = [[Treaty of the Pyrenees]] <br/> Marriage contract between [[Louis_XIV_of_France|Louis XIV]] and [[Maria Theresa of Spain]]\n|combatant1 = {{flagcountry|Kingdom of France}} <br/> {{flagcountry|Dutch Republic}} (to 1648) <br/> {{flagcountry|Commonwealth of England}} (from 1654) <br/> {{flagcountry|Portugal|1707}} <br/> [[File:Flag of Catalonia.svg|24px]] [[Principality of Catalonia]] (1640-1641)\n|combatant2  = {{flagicon|Spain|1506}} [[Habsburg Spain|Spain]] <br/> {{flagcountry|Holy Roman Empire}} (to 1648)\n|commander1  = \n*{{flagicon|Kingdom of France}} [[Henri de la Tour d'Auvergne, Vicomte de Turenne|Turenne]]\n*{{flagicon|Kingdom of France}} [[Louis II de Bourbon, Prince of Cond\u00e9|Cond\u00e9]] (pre-1652)\n*{{flagicon|Kingdom of France}} [[Jean de Gassion|Gassion]]\n*{{flagicon|Kingdom of France}} [[Caesar, duc de Choiseul|Choiseul]]\n*{{flagicon|Kingdom of France}} [[Charles de La Porte|La Meilleraye]]\n*{{flagicon|Kingdom of France}} [[Henri de La Fert\u00e9-Senneterre|La Fert\u00e9]]\n*{{flagicon|Kingdom of France}} [[Henri_de_Sourdis|De Sourdis]]\n*[[File:Gro\u00dfherzogin Sachsen Weimar.jpg|left|15px|]] [[Bernard of Saxe-Weimar]]\n|commander2=\n*{{flagicon|Spain|1506}} [[Cardinal-Infante Ferdinand]]\n*{{flagicon|Spain|1506}} [[Francisco de Melo]]\n*{{flagicon|Holy Roman Empire}} [[Archduke_Leopold_Wilhelm_of_Austria|Leopold Wilhelm]]\n*{{flagicon|Spain|1506}} [[John of Austria the Younger|John of Austria]]\n*{{flagicon|Spain|1506}} [[Luis de Benavides Carrillo, Marquis of Caracena|Caracena]]\n*{{flagicon|Spain|1506}} [[Pedro Fajardo, 5th Marquis of Los V\u00e9lez|V\u00e9lez]]\n*{{flagicon|Kingdom of France}} [[Louis II de Bourbon, Prince de Cond\u00e9|Cond\u00e9]] (post-1652)\n|strength1= {{circa}} 100,000 (1640s){{efn|The strength of the French Army fluctuated greatly in the 1640s, and estimates by historians vary accordingly, ranging from 218,000 to just 40,000 around 1645\u20131648.{{sfn|Chartrand|2019|p=33}} On average, it is likely that about 100,000 soldiers were usually in the field at the time.{{sfn|Chartrand|2019|p=24}} }}<br/>{{circa}} 120,000 (1653){{sfn|Chartrand|2019|p=33}}<br/>{{circa}} 110,000\u2013125,000 (1653\u20131659){{sfn|Chartrand|2019|p=34}}\n|strength2=Unknown\n|casualties1  = {{flagicon|Kingdom of France}} 200,000\u2013300,000 killed or wounded{{sfn|Wilson|2009|p= }}\n|casualties2  = Unknown\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Franco-Spanish War (1635\u20131659)}}\n{{Campaignbox Franco-Spanish wars}}\n{{Campaignbox Thirty Years' War}}\n\nThe '''Franco-Spanish War''' (1635\u20131659) was a military conflict that was the result of [[France|French]] involvement in the [[Thirty Years' War]]. After [[History of Sweden (1611\u201348)|the German allies of Sweden]] were forced to seek terms with the [[Holy Roman Empire]], the French first minister, [[Cardinal Richelieu]], declared war on [[Habsburg Spain|Spain]] because French territory was surrounded by [[Habsburg]] territories. The conflict was a continuation of the aims of the [[War of the Mantuan Succession]] (1628\u201331) in which France invaded northern Italy trying to take possession of territory claimed by the [[Spanish Habsburg]]s. Though some minor territorial gains were made by France, the Franco-Spanish War ended inconclusively in 1659 with the [[Treaty of the Pyrenees]].<ref>Parrott, David: ''Richelieu's Army: War, Government and Society in France, 1624\u20131642''. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 2003. {{ISBN|0521792096}}, pp. 77\u201378. ''France's War against Habsburgs, 1624-1659: the Politics of Military Failure'' in Garc\u00eda Hernan, Enrique; Maffi, Davide: ''Guerra y Sociedad en La Monarqu\u00eda Hisp\u00e1nica: Politica, Estrategia y Cultura en la Europa Moderna (1500-1700''), 2 vols; Madrid: Laberinto, 2006. {{ISBN|9788400084912}}, pp. 31-49.</ref><ref>Darby, Graham: ''Spain in the Seventeenth Century''. London: Longman, 1995. {{ISBN|9780582072343}}, p. 66.</ref><ref>Luard, Evan: ''War in International Society: A Study in International Sociology''. London: Tauris, 1986, p. 50. {{ISBN|9781850430124}}. Black, Jeremy: ''The Origins of War in Early Modern Europe''. Edinburgh: J. Donald, 1987, p. 106. {{ISBN|9780859761680}}</ref>\n\nMain areas of conflict included [[Northern Italy]], the [[Spanish Netherlands]], [[Catalonia]], and the [[Rhineland]], with both sides backing domestic conspiracies in the other. Spain financed [[Huguenot rebellions]] from 1622 to 1630, and the 1648 to 1653 civil war known as the [[Fronde]]; France supported revolts against Spanish rule in [[Portuguese_Restoration_War|Portugal]], [[Reapers' War|Catalonia]] and [[Neapolitan Republic (1647)|Naples]]. \n\nThe war consisted of two distinct phases; before 1635, France supported Habsburg opponents in the Dutch Revolt and Thirty Years War, but avoided direct involvement. After agreeing alliances with the [[Swedish_Empire|Swedes]] and [[Dutch_Republic|Dutch]] in 1635, it became a participant in both wars, which ended with the 1648 [[Peace of Westphalia]]. The hostilities of the war ended with the marriage of [[Louis XIV of France]] and [[Maria Theresa of Spain]], eldest daughter of [[Philip IV of Spain|Philip IV]]. Spain remained a great global power, with a vast colonial empire, but the war is often seen as the beginning of the Spanish decline as the pre-eminent superpower.{{sfn|Parrott|2001|pp=77-78}}\n\n==Strategic Overview==\n17th century Europe was dominated by the struggle between the [[House_of_Bourbon|Bourbon]] kings of [[Kingdom_of_France|France]], and their [[House_of_Habsburg|Habsburg]] rivals in [[Habsburg_Spain|Spain]] and the [[Holy Roman Empire]]. Until the mid 20th century, the [[Thirty Years War]] was primarily seen as a German religious conflict; in 1938, historian [[Veronica_Wedgwood|CV Wedgwood]] argued it formed part of a wider, ongoing European struggle, with the Habsburg-Bourbon conflict at its centre. A perspective now generally accepted by historians, its implication is that strategies pursued during the Franco-Spanish War can only be understood in a European context.{{sfn|Sutherland|1992|pages=588-590}}   \n\nIn 1630, Habsburg possessions bordered France in the [[Spanish Netherlands]], [[Franche-Comt\u00e9]], [[Alsace]], [[Roussillon]] and [[Duchy_of_Lorraine|Lorraine]] (see Map). France supported anti-Spanish wars by the [[Eighty_Years'_War|Dutch]], and clients in [[Lombardy|Northern Italy]], as well as revolts in [[Portuguese_Restoration_War|Portugal]], [[Reapers' War|Catalonia]] and [[Kingdom_of_Naples|Naples]]. French-backed Austrian opponents included the [[Franco-Ottoman_alliance|Ottomans]], the [[Venetian Republic]], [[George_I_R\u00e1k\u00f3czi|Transylvanian rebels]], and [[Swedish_Empire|Sweden]].{{sfn|Jensen|1985|pp=451-470}} \n[[File:France 1552-1798.png|thumb|left|upright=1.25|France 1552-1798]]\nSpain and Austria financed Huguenot rebellions in South-Western France, and the 1648 to 1653 civil war known as the [[Fronde]]. They also backed conspiracies led by the feudal lords who resented their loss of power under [[Cardinal_Richelieu|Richelieu]] and [[Cardinal Mazarin]]; the most significant included the 1632 [[Henri_II_de_Montmorency|Montmorency plot]], the [[Louis,_Count_of_Soissons|1641 Princes des Paix rising]], and [[Henri_Coiffier_de_Ruz\u00e9,_Marquis_of_Cinq-Mars|Cinq-Mars]] in 1642.{{sfn|Wilson|2009|pages=663-664}} \n\nWider co-operation between the Habsburgs was limited, since their objectives did not always align; Spain was a global maritime power, Austria primarily a European land power. The Empire had over 1,800 members, most extremely small; although a Habsburg had been [[Holy Roman Emperor]] since 1440, in theory it was an elected position. After [[Peace_of_Augsburg|1555]], the Empire increasingly became a federation of independent states; encouraged by France, Habsburg acceptance of this reality is one of the less acknowledged outcomes of the 1648 [[Treaty of Westphalia]].{{sfn|Wilson|1976|p=259}}\n\nFrance faced the same issue of diverging objectives with its allies. The war coincided with the period of economic supremacy known as the [[Dutch Golden Age]], and by 1640, many Dutch statesmen viewed French ambitions in the Spanish Netherlands as a threat.{{sfn|Wilson|2009|p=669}} Unlike France, Swedish war aims were restricted to Germany, and in 1641, they considered a separate peace with Ferdinand.{{sfn|Wilson|2009|p=627}}         \n\nMuch of the fighting took place around the [[Spanish Road]], an overland supply route connecting Spanish possessions in [[Piedmont|Northern Italy]] to [[Flanders]]. Rarely used for moving soldiers post-1601, it remained vital for trade, and went through areas like [[Alsace]] essential to French security. In Northern Italy, [[Duchy_of_Savoy|Savoy]] and the Spanish-held [[Duchy of Milan]] were strategically important, since they provided access to the vulnerable southern borders of France, and Habsburg [[Erblande|territories in Austria]]. Richelieu aimed to end Spanish dominance in these areas, an objective largely achieved by the time he died in 1642.{{sfn|Wilson|1976|p=259}}    \n\nUntil the advent of railways in the 19th century, water was the primary means of bulk transportation, and campaigns focused on control of rivers and ports. Armies relied on [[Military_logistics|foraging]], while feeding the draught animals essential for transport and cavalry restricted campaigning in the winter. By the 1630s, the countryside had been devastated by years of constant warfare, which limited the size of armies, and the ability to conduct operations. Sickness killed far more soldiers than battle; France invaded [[Flanders]] with 27,000 men in May, which was reduced by desertion and disease to under 17,000 in early July.{{sfn|Van Nimwegen|2014|pp=169-170}}\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Philip IV of Spain - Vel\u00e1zquez 1644.jpg|thumb|right|upright|[[Philip_IV_of_Spain|Philip IV of Spain]], ruler from 1621 to 1665]]\nThe [[Thirty Years War]] began in 1618 when the [[Protestantism|Protestant]]-dominated [[Bohemian_Revolt|Bohemian Estates]] offered the [[Kingdom_of_Bohemia|Crown of Bohemia]] to [[Frederick_V_of_the_Palatinate|Frederick of the Palatinate]], rather than the conservative [[Catholic_Church|Catholic]], [[Ferdinand_II,_Holy_Roman_Emperor#Bohemian_revolt|Emperor Ferdinand II]]. Most of the [[Holy Roman Empire]] remained neutral, viewing it as an inheritance dispute, and the revolt was quickly suppressed. However, when Frederick refused to admit defeat, Imperial forces invaded the [[Palatinate_campaign|Palatinate]] and forced him into exile; removal of a hereditary prince changed the nature and extent of the war.{{sfn|Wilson|2009|pp=314-316}}  \n\nAccompanied by a renewed [[Counter-Reformation]], this threatened Protestant states within the Empire. It also drew in external powers who held Imperial territories; [[County_of_Nassau#County_of_Nassau-Dillenburg|Nassau-Dillenburg]] was a hereditary possession of the [[Prince_of_Orange|Dutch Prince of Orange]], while [[Christian_IV_of_Denmark|Christian IV of Denmark]] was also [[Duke_of_Holstein-Gottorp|Duke of Holstein]]. With France facing Spanish-financed [[Huguenot rebellions]] from 1622 to 1630, and [[War_of_the_Mantuan_Succession|proxy wars in Italy]] from 1628 to 1631, this provided opportunities to weaken the Habsburgs, but avoid direct conflict.{{sfn|Hayden|1973|pp=1-23}}\n\nFrance supported the Dutch war with Spain, as well as funding [[Denmark\u2013Norway|Danish]], then [[Swedish_Empire|Swedish]] intervention in the Empire. In 1630, [[Gustavus Adolphus of Sweden]] invaded [[Pomerania]]; partly to support his Protestant co-religionists, he also sought control of the [[Baltic_maritime_trade_(c._1400\u20131800)|Baltic trade]], which provided much of Sweden's income.{{sfn|Wedgwood|1938|pp=385-386}} Economic issues meant Swedish intervention continued after Gustavus was killed in 1632, but led to conflict with [[Electorate_of_Saxony|Saxony]], [[Brandenburg-Prussia]] and Denmark-Norway. Defeat at [[Battle of N\u00f6rdlingen (1634)|N\u00f6rdlingen]] in September 1634 forced the Swedes to retreat, while most of their German allies made peace with Ferdinand in the 1635 [[Treaty of Prague (1635)|Treaty of Prague]].{{sfn|Knox|2017|pp=182-183}} \n[[File:Luis XIII, rey de Francia (Philippe de Champaigne).jpg|thumb|left|upright|[[Louis_XIII_of_France|Louis XIII]], French ruler from 1610 to 1643]]\nThe other major European conflict of the period was the 1568 to 1648 [[Eighty Years' War]] between Spain and the [[Dutch Republic]], suspended in 1609 by the [[Twelve Years' Truce]].{{sfn|Lynch|1969|p=42}} The Spanish strongly objected to its commercial provisions and when [[Philip_IV_of_Spain|Philip IV]] became king in 1621, he resumed the war. The cost proved extremely high, increased after 1628 by a proxy war with France over the [[War_of_the_Mantuan_Succession|Mantuan succession]]. While the [[Spanish Empire]] reached its maximum extent under Philip's rule, its complexity and size made it increasingly difficult to govern, or enact essential reforms.{{sfn|Mackay|1999|pp=4-5}}\n\nIn 1628, the Dutch captured the [[Battle_in_the_Bay_of_Matanzas|Spanish treasure fleet]], which they used to finance the 1629 [[Siege_of_'s-Hertogenbosch|capture of 's-Hertogenbosch]]. The powerful [[Amsterdam]] mercantile lobby saw this as an opportunity to end the war; negotiations ended without result in 1633, but strengthened the peace party.{{sfn|Israel|1995|pp=521-523}} The Peace of Prague led to rumours of a proposed Austro-Spanish offensive in the Netherlands, leading [[Louis_XIII_of_France|Louis XIII]] and Richelieu to decide on direct intervention. In early 1635, they signed an agreement with [[Bernard of Saxe-Weimar]] to provide 16,000 troops for a campaign in Alsace and the Rhineland, an anti-Spain alliance with the [[Dutch Republic]], and the Treaty of Compi\u00e8gne with Sweden.{{sfn|Poot|2013|pp=120-122}}\n\n==Phase I; 1635 to the 1648 Treaty of Westphalia==\n{{Location map many|Belgium|caption = 1635-1659; key locations Northern France and the Spanish Netherlands (current Belgium borders shown)|relief=yes|border = black| width = 260| float = right\n|label =  Les Avins|pos=left|lat_deg= 50|lat_min= 34|lon_deg = 5|lon_min = 17\n|label3 = Dunkirk |pos3= right|lat3_deg=51|lat3_min = 02|lon3_deg = 2|lon3_min = 23\n|label5 = Brussels|pos5=left|lat5_deg=50|lat5_min =51 |lon5_deg = 4 |lon5_min = 21\n|label6 = Leuven|pos6=top|lat6_deg=50|lat6_min =53 |lon6_deg = 4 |lon6_min = 42\n|label7=  Valenciennes|pos7= right|lat7_deg = 50|lat7_min = 21|lon7_deg = 3|lon7_min = 34\n|label8 = Maastricht|pos8 = right|lat8_deg = 50 | lat8_min = 51 | lon8_deg = 5 | lon8_min = 41\n|label9= Corbie|pos9 = top|lat9_deg = 50|lat9_min = 00|lon9_deg = 2 | lon9_min = 30\n|label10= Lens|pos10 = top|lat10_deg = 50|lat10_min = 33|lon10_deg = 3 | lon10_min = 54\n|label11= Arras|pos11=right|lat11_deg=50|lat11_min = 18|lon11_deg = 2|lon11_min = 47\n}}\nIn May, a French army of 27,000 advanced into the Spanish Netherlands, defeating a smaller Spanish force at [[Battle of Les Avins|Les Avins]], before linking up with the Dutch. Outnumbered, the [[Cardinal-Infante_Ferdinand_of_Austria|Cardinal-Infante]] withdrew into [[Leuven]]; by the time the [[Siege_of_Leuven|siege began]] on 24 June, desertions reduced the French to under 17,000, and they withdrew in early July. After the loss of [[Siege_of_Schenkenschans|Schenkenschans]] on 28 July, the Dutch also withdrew from the Spanish Netherlands.{{sfn|Van Nimwegen|2014|pp=169-170}} \n\nThis failure meant the [[States_General_of_the_Netherlands|States-General]] opposed further large scale land operations, and instead prioritised attacks on Spanish trade.{{sfn|Israel|1995|p=934}} In 1636, a Spanish offensive reached [[Corbie]] in Northern France; although it caused panic in [[Paris]], lack of supplies forced them to retreat, and it was not repeated. Spain's focus was to recover territories in the [[Low Countries]], and repulse [[Battle_of_Tornavento|Franco-Savoyard attacks in Lombardy]].{{sfn|Israel|1995|pp=272-273}}       \n\nAs agreed at Compi\u00e8gne in 1635, the French replaced Swedish garrisons in Alsace; prior to his death in 1639, Bernard of Saxe-Weimar won a series of victories in the Rhineland, the most important being the [[Battle_of_Breisach|capture of Breisach]] in December 1638.{{sfn|Bely|2014|pp=94-95}} This severed the Spanish Road, forcing Spain to reinforce their armies by sea, where the Dutch had maritime supremacy; in 1639, they destroyed a large supply convoy at [[Battle_of_the_Downs|the Downs]]. They also attacked [[Portuguese_Empire|Portuguese possessions]] in Africa and the Americas, then part of the Spanish Empire; [[Madrid]]'s inability to prevent this caused increasing unrest in Portugal.{{sfn|Costa|2005|p=4}}\n{{Location map many|Baden-W\u00fcrttemberg|caption = 1635-1648; key locations Rhineland campaign|relief=yes|border = black| width = 200| float = left\n|label =  Breisach|pos=right|lat_deg= 48|lat_min= 02|lon_deg = 7|lon_min = 35\n|label5 = Rheinfelden|pos5=right|lat5_deg=47|lat5_min =33 |lon5_deg = 7 |lon5_min = 48\n|label6 = Mergentheim |pos6=bottom  |lat6_deg=49|lat6_min =30|lon6_deg = 09|lon6_min = 46\n|label7=  Mannheim|pos7= left|lat7_deg = 49|lat7_min = 29|lon7_deg = 8|lon7_min = 28\n|label8 = Tuttlingen|pos8 = right|lat8_deg = 47 | lat8_min = 59 | lon8_deg = 8 | lon8_min = 49\n|label9= Zusmarshausen|pos9 = left|lat9_deg = 48|lat9_min = 23|lon9_deg = 10 | lon9_min = 35\n|label10= N\u00f6rdlingen |pos10 = left|lat10_deg = 48|lat10_min = 51|lon10_deg = 10| lon10_min = 29\n}}\nThroughout the 1630s, attempts by the [[Crown of Castile]] to increase taxes and centralise control led to protests; in 1640, these became revolts in [[Portuguese_Restoration_War|Portugal]] and [[Reapers'_War|Catalonia]]. In 1641, the [[Catalan Courts]] recognised Louis XIII as [[Count of Barcelona]], and ruler of the [[Principality of Catalonia]].{{sfn|Van Gelderen|2002|p=284}} However, Catalans found French administration differed little from that of Castile, and the war became a three sided contest between the rural peasantry, the Spanish, and the French and Catalan elite.{{sfn|Mitchell|2005|pp=431-448}}\n\nOn 14 May 1643, Louis XIII died; his five year old son, [[Louis_XIV_of_France|Louis XIV]], became king, his mother, [[Anne of Austria]], taking control of the Regency Council that ruled in his name. Five days later, [[Louis II de Bourbon, Prince of Cond\u00e9|Cond\u00e9, then known as the duc d'Enghien]], defeated the Spanish [[Army of Flanders]] at [[Battle of Rocroi|Rocroi]]; less decisive than often thought, the loss of this highly experienced unit ended Spanish dominance of the European battlefield.{{sfn|Black|2002|p=147}} Cond\u00e9, a member of the royal family, and effective ruler of large parts of eastern France, used it as leverage in his struggle for political control with Anne, and [[Cardinal Mazarin]].{{sfn|Wilson|2009|pp=666-668}}\n\nDespite limited success in Northern France and the Spanish Netherlands, including victory at [[Battle of Lens|Lens]] in August 1648, France was unable to knock Spain out of the war. In Germany, Imperial victories at [[Battle_of_Tuttlingen|Tuttlingen]] and [[Battle_of_Herbsthausen|Mergentheim]] were offset by French success at [[Battle_of_N\u00f6rdlingen_(1645)|N\u00f6rdlingen]] and [[Battle_of_Zusmarshausen|Zusmarshausen]]. In Italy, Franco-Savoyard offensives against the Spanish-ruled [[Duchy of Milan]] achieved little, partly due to the disruption caused by the 1639 to 1642 [[Piedmontese Civil War]]. Victory at [[Battle_of_Orbetello|Orbetello]] in June 1646, and the recapture of [[Neapolitan_Republic_(1647)|Naples]] in 1647 left Spain firmly in control of this region.{{sfn|Paoletti|2007|pp=27-28}}\n\nThe 1648 [[Peace of Westphalia]] ended the Thirty Years War and recognised Dutch independence, ending the drain on Spanish resources. Under the October 1648 Treaty of M\u00fcnster, France gained strategic locations in Alsace and Lorraine, as well as [[Pinerolo]], which controlled access to Alpine passes in Northern Italy.{{sfn|Paoletti |2007|pp=27-28}} However, the peace excluded Italy, [[Burgundian_Circle|Imperial territories in the Low Countries]], and French-occupied [[Duchy_of_Lorraine|Lorraine]], while Emperor Ferdinand agreed to remain neutral. This meant fighting continued.{{sfn|Wilson|2009|p=747}}\n\n==Phase II; 1648 to 1659==\n{{Location map many|Italy North|caption = Northern Italy; key locations 1635-1659 (note Pinerolo, ceded to France in 1648) |border = black|width =360|float = right|relief = yes|Italy Piedmont#Italy\n|label   = Tornavento    |pos = left    |lat_deg   =45|lat_min =35|lon_deg  = 8 |lon_min = 43\n|label2  = Turin         |pos2= top   |lat2_deg  =45|lat2_min=05|lon2_deg  = 7|lon2_min = 41\n|label3  = Mantua        |pos3 = right |lat3_deg  =45|lat3_min=09|lon3_deg  =10|lon3_min = 47\n|label4  = Casale        |pos4 = top   |lat4_deg  =45|lat4_min=08|lon4_deg  = 8|lon4_min = 27\n|label5  = Milan         |pos5 = right   |lat5_deg  =45|lat5_min=28|lon5_deg = 9 |lon5_min = 11\n|label6  = Cremona       |pos6 = bottom  |lat6_deg  =45|lat6_min=08|lon6_deg = 10|lon6_min = 02\n|label7  = Pinerolo      |pos7 = bottom   |lat7_deg  =44|lat7_min=53|lon7_deg  = 7|lon7_min = 20\n|label8  = Genoa         |pos8 = bottom |lat8_deg  =44|lat8_min=24|lon8_deg = 08|lon8_min = 56\n|label9  = Modena        |pos9 = bottom |lat9_deg  =44|lat9_min=39|lon9_deg = 10|lon9_min = 56\n}}\nBy 1648, both sides were under increasing financial strain, forcing Philip to prioritise Catalonia, although he nonetheless had to declare bankruptcy in 1647 and 1653.{{sfn|Inglis Jones|1994|pp=59-64}} A combination of political conflict and economic stress led to the 1648 to 1653 French civil war known as the [[Fronde]]; in 1651, Mazarin forced Cond\u00e9 into exile in the Spanish Netherlands, where he signed an alliance with Philip. He was replaced by [[Henri_de_La_Tour_d'Auvergne,_Viscount_of_Turenne|Turenne]], also a talented commander, but far less powerful politically.{{sfn|Inglis Jones|1994|pp=9-12}} \n\nSpain [[Siege_of_Barcelona_(1651)|recaptured Barcelona]] in October 1652, and although fighting continued in [[Rousillon]], by 1653 the front had stabilised along the modern [[Pyrenees]] border.{{sfn|Parker|1972|pp=221-224}} After the Fronde ended in 1653, France resumed attempts to capture Milan, which provided access to the vulnerable southern border of Habsburg [[Erblande|territories in Austria]]. Despite support from Savoy, the [[Francesco_I_d'Este,_Duke_of_Modena|Duke of Modena]] and Portugal, they failed to achieve this.{{sfn|Schneid|2012|p=69}}\n\nBy now, the two antagonists were exhausted, and neither could establish dominance over the other. From 1654 to 1656, French victories at [[Battle of Arras (1654)|Arras]], [[Landrecies]] and [[Saint-Ghislain]] were offset by Spanish success at [[Pavia|Pavia, in Lombardy]], and [[Battle of Valenciennes (1656)|Valenciennes]]. Under pressure from [[Pope Alexander VII]], Mazarin offered peace terms, but refused to accept Spain's insistence Cond\u00e9 must be restored to his French titles and lands.{{sfn|Inglis Jones|1994|pp=296-300}} Philip viewed this as a personal obligation, and with the war apparently going his way, rejected talks.{{sfn|Black|1991|p=16}}    \n\nPrior to the 1660s, France lacked a powerful navy of its own, and instead relied on the Dutch, who ceased to provide this after 1648. Since 1654, Spain had been involved in a [[Anglo-Spanish_War_(1654\u20131660)|naval conflict]] with the [[Commonwealth_of_England|English Commonwealth]], and in 1657, Mazarin negotiated an [[Treaty_of_Paris_(1657)|Anglo-French alliance]]. France was required to end its backing for the exiled [[Charles_II_of_England|Charles II]], some of whose supporters joined the Spanish as a result.{{sfn|Quainton |1935|p=268}} \n\n1658 featured an Anglo-French offensive in North Flanders, whose main objective was [[Dunkirk]], a centre for Spanish [[privateer]] attacks on English shipping.{{efn|Its location meant ships based in Dunkirk could enter the [[North Sea]] on a single flood tide, allowing them to raid as far north as the [[Orkney|Orkney Islands]]; its closure was a British objective for centuries.{{sfn|Bromley |1987|p=233}}}} After the [[Siege_of_Dunkirk_(1658)|loss of Dunkirk]] in June, Spain requested a truce, which Mazarin initially refused. However, Cromwell's death led to political chaos in England, while French allies Savoy and [[Duchy_of_Modena_and_Reggio|Modena]] ended the war in Northern Italy by agreeing a truce with the Spanish commander, [[Luis de Benavides Carrillo, Marquis of Caracena|Caracena]].{{sfn|Hanlon|2016|p=134}}\n\n==Treaty of the Pyrenees and marriage contract==\n[[File:Louis, Grand Cond\u00e9.PNG|thumb|left|upright|[[Louis II de Bourbon, Prince of Cond\u00e9|Cond\u00e9]]; exiled in 1651, his restoration was a major obstacle to peace]]\nOn 8 May 1659, France and Spain began negotiating terms; the death of [[Oliver Cromwell]] in September 1658 weakened England, which was allowed to observe, but excluded from the talks. Although the [[Anglo-Spanish_War_(1654\u20131660)|Anglo-Spanish War]] was suspended after the 1660 [[The_Restoration|restoration of Charles II]], it did not formally end until the 1667 [[Treaty_of_Madrid_(1667)|Treaty of Madrid]].{{sfn|Davenport| Paullin|1917|p=50}}\n\nUnder the [[Treaty of the Pyrenees]], signed on November 5, 1659, France gained [[Artois]] and [[French_Hainaut|Hainaut]] along its border with the Spanish Netherlands, as well as [[Northern_Catalonia|Roussillon, or Northern Catalonia]]. These were more significant than often assumed; in combination with the 1648 Treaty of M\u00fcnster, France strengthened its borders in the east and south-west, while in 1662, Charles II [[Sale_of_Dunkirk|sold Dunkirk to France]]. Acquisition of Roussillon established the Franco-Spanish border along the [[Pyrenees]], but divided the historic [[Principality of Catalonia]], commemorated each year by French Catalan-speakers in Perpignan.{{sfn|Serra|2008|pp=82-84}}     \n\nFrance withdrew support from [[Afonso VI of Portugal]], while Louis XIV renounced his claim to be Count of Barcelona, and king of Catalonia. Cond\u00e9 regained his possessions and titles, as did many of his followers, such as the [[Charles de Montsaulnin, Comte de Montal|Comte de Montal]], but his political power was broken, and he did not hold military command again until 1667.{{sfn|Tucker |2011|p=838}} \n[[Image:Diego Vel\u00e1zquez 030b.jpg|thumb|right|upright|[[Portrait of the Infanta Maria Theresa of Spain|Maria Theresa]], whose marriage to Louis XIV was part of the peace negotiations]]\nAn integral part of the peace negotiations was the marriage contract between Louis and Maria Theresa, which he used to justify the 1666 to 1667 [[War of Devolution]], and formed the basis of French claims over the next 50 years. The marriage was more significant than intended, since it was agreed shortly after Philip's second wife, [[Mariana of Austria]], gave birth to a second son, both of whom died young.{{sfn|Inglis Jones|1994|p=307}} Philip died in 1665, leaving his four year old son [[Charles_II_of_Spain|Charles]] as king, once described as \"always on the verge of death, but repeatedly baffling Christendom by continuing to live.\"{{sfn|Durant|Durant|1963|p=25}}\n\n==Aftermath and historical assessment==\n\nWhile the war came to be seen as marking the begin of Spanish \"decline\" in Europe this was not apparent at the time; combined with the 1648 treaty, France made crucial strategic gains around its borders, but modern assessments suggest a more balanced perspective. \n\n\"The (1659 treaty) was a peace of equals. Spanish losses were not great, and France returned some territory and strongholds. With hindsight, historians have regarded the treaty as a symbol of the 'decline of Spain' and the 'ascendancy of France'; at that time, however, (it) appeared a far from decisive verdict on the international hierarchy\".{{sfn|Darby |2015|p=66}}\n\n\"Spain maintained her supremacy in Europe until 1659, and was the greatest imperial power for years after that. Although (its) economic and military power suffered an abrupt decline in the half century after the Peace of the Pyrenees, (it) was a major participant in the European coalitions against Louis XIV, and the peace congresses at [[Treaties_of_Nijmegen|Nijmegen]] in 1678, and [[Peace_of_Ryswick|Ryswick]] in 1697\".{{sfn|Levy|1983|p=34}}\n\n\"The treaties of Westphalia and the Pyrenees were more obviously a compromise reflecting an existing balance of forces than a military diktat imposed by victorious powers\".<ref>Parrott, David: ''Richelieu's Army: War, Government and Society in France, 1624\u20131642''. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 2003. {{ISBN|0521792096}}, pp. 77\u201378.</ref> There, he labels France's war against Spain as \"25 years of indecisive, over-ambitious and, on occasions, truly disastrous conflict\".<ref>'France's War against Habsburgs, 1624-1659: the Politics of Military Failure'' in Garc\u00eda Hernan, Enrique; Maffi, Davide: ''Guerra y Sociedad en La Monarqu\u00eda Hisp\u00e1nica: Politica, Estrategia y Cultura en la Europa Moderna (1500-1700''), 2 vols; Madrid: Laberinto, 2006. {{ISBN|9788400084912}}, pp. 31-49.</ref>\n\nR.A. Stradling states that despite the French victory at the Battle of the Dunes, \"The subsequent negotiations resulted in a peace settlement in which both sides made concessions\". He also cites Antonio Dom\u00ednguez Ortiz's ''The Golden Age of Spain, 1516\u20131659'' (1971) to reflect the stalemate: \"It is certain that if in 1659 France had not moderated its demands the contest would have been continued interminably.\" <ref>Stradling, R.A.: ''Spain's Struggle For Europe, 1598-1668''. London: The Hambledon Press, 1994. {{ISBN|9781852850890}}, p. 27.</ref>\n\n\"The other consequence was that many of the wars of this age had only inconclusive results. Spain and France settled for such a draw in 1659, with a virtually equal exchange of the main territories\".<ref>Luard, Evan: ''War in International Society: A Study in International Sociology''. London: Tauris, 1986, p. 50. {{ISBN|9781850430124}}</ref> \"The result was the inconclusive conflict which dragged through to 1659\".<ref>Black, Jeremy: ''The Origins of War in Early Modern Europe''. Edinburgh: J. Donald, 1987, p. 106. {{ISBN|9780859761680}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{cite book |last1=Bely |first1=Lucien |editor-last1=Asbach |editor-first1=Olaf |editor-last2= Schr\u00f6der |editor-first2= Peter |title=France and the Thirty Years War in The Ashgate Research Companion to the Thirty Years' War |date=2014 |publisher=Ashgate |isbn=978-1409406297 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Black |first1=Jeremy |title=European Warfare, 1494-1660 (Warfare and History) |date=2002 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-0415275316 |authorlink=Jeremy_Black_(historian)|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Black |first1=Jeremy |title=A Military Revolutio