{"title_page": "Lake Mills, Wisconsin", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Lake Mills, Wisconsin\n|settlement_type          = [[City]]\n|nickname                 = \n|motto                    = \n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline            = Bandshelter.jpg\n|image_caption = Franklin Else Bandstand in Commons Park\n|imagesize                = \n|image_flag               = \n|image_seal               = \n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|pushpin_map              = USA Wisconsin\n|pushpin_mapsize          = 250px\n|pushpin_map_caption      = Location of Lake Mills within Wisconsin\n\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = {{flag|United States}}\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = {{flag|Wisconsin}}\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Wisconsin|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Jefferson County, Wisconsin|Jefferson]]\n\n<!-- Government -->\n|government_footnotes     = \n|government_type          = City Council\n|leader_title             = \n|leader_name              = \n|leader_title1            = \n|leader_name1             = \n|established_title        = \n|established_date         = \n\n<!-- Area -->\n|unit_pref                = Imperial\n|area_footnotes           = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web|title=2018 U.S. Gazetteer Files|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2018_Gazetteer/2018_gaz_place_55.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=Feb 15, 2020}}</ref>\n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_total_km2           = 11.53\n|area_land_km2            = 10.72\n|area_water_km2           = 0.81\n|area_total_sq_mi         = 4.45\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 4.14\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 0.31\n\n<!-- Population -->\n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_est           = 5923\n|pop_est_as_of            = 2018\n|population_footnotes     = <ref name =\"wwwcensusgov\"/>\n|population_total         = 5708\n|population_density_km2   = 552.35\n|population_density_sq_mi = 1430.68\n\n<!-- General information -->\n|timezone                 = [[North American Central Time Zone|Central (CST)]]\n|utc_offset               = -6\n|timezone_DST             = CDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -5\n|elevation_footnotes      = \n|elevation_m              = \n|elevation_ft             = \n|coordinates              = {{coord|43|4|48|N|88|54|33|W|region:US_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type         = [[Zip Code]]\n|postal_code              = 53551\n|area_code                = [[Area code 920|920]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standards|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 55-41675\n|blank1_name              = \n|blank1_info              = \n|website                  = {{URL|www.ci.lake-mills.wi.us}}\n|footnotes                = \n|pop_est_footnotes = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018CenPopScriptOnlyDirtyFixDoNotUse\"/>\n|image_map = File:Jefferson County Wisconsin Incorporated and Unincorporated areas Lake Mills Highlighted.svg\n|map_caption = Location of Lake Mills in Jefferson County, Wisconsin.\n}}\n\n'''Lake Mills''' is a city in [[Jefferson County, Wisconsin|Jefferson County]], [[Wisconsin]], United States. The population was 5,708 at the 2010 census.<ref name=\"Census 2010\">{{Cite web| url=https://www.census.gov| title=Profile of General Population and Housing Characteristics: 2010 Demographic Profile Data (DP-1): Lake Mills city, Wisconsin| publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]| accessdate=October 4, 2012}}</ref> The city is located partially within the [[Lake Mills (town), Wisconsin|Town of Lake Mills]].\n\n==History==\nLake Mills occupies the east shore of Rock Lake. The area was first settled by Captain Joseph Keyes. He called it \"Lake Mills\", after a [[saw mill]] and [[grist mill]] operating using power from nearby [[Rock Lake (Wisconsin)|Rock Lake]].<ref>{{cite book | url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_9V1IAAAAMAAJ | title=The Origin of Certain Place Names in the United States | publisher=[[United States Government Publishing Office|Government Printing Office]] | author=Gannett, Henry | year=1905 | pages=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_9V1IAAAAMAAJ/page/n178 179]}}</ref><ref>\"[http://www.wisconsinhistory.org/dictionary/index.asp?action=view&term_id=3463 Lake Mills &#91;origin of place name&#93;]\". ''Dictionary of Wisconsin History''.</ref>\n\nLake Mills was chartered in 1836, and the first building was built in 1837. The village of Lake Mills incorporated in 1852 out of the surrounding [[Lake Mills (town), Wisconsin|town of Lake Mills]]. In 1866 the village changed its name to \"Tyrahnena\", but changed it back again to \"Lake Mills\" the next year.<ref>\"An Act to consolidate and amend an act entitled 'an act to incorporate the village of Lake Mills,' and the several acts amendatory thereof, and to change the name of the village of Lake Mills to the village of Tyrahnena.\" in ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=lvbRAAAAMAAJ&lpg=PA378&ots=lm_PjpRuFx Private and Local Laws Passed by the Legislature of Wisconsin in the Year 1866]'', Chapter 188. April 13, 1866.</ref><ref>William J. Anderson and William A. Anderson (eds.). ''[http://digicoll.library.wisc.edu/cgi-bin/WI/WI-idx?type=goto&id=WI.WIBlueBk1929&page=629&isize=L The Wisconsin Blue Book 1929]''. Madison: Democrat Printing Co., 1929, p. 629.</ref> (''Tyrahnena'', or ''Tyranena'', is supposedly an indigenous name meaning \"sparkling waters\".)<ref>Lake Mills Chamber of Commerce. \"[http://www.vandregraphicdesign.com/vandreportshort/images/LM_Chamberbrochurefinal1.24.05std.pdf Legendary Lake Mills] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081013162008/http://www.vandregraphicdesign.com/vandreportshort/images/LM_Chamberbrochurefinal1.24.05std.pdf |date=2008-10-13 }}\".</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nLake Mills is located at {{coord|43|4|48|N|88|54|33|W|region:US_type:city}} (43.080108, -88.909209).<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geographies/reference-files/time-series/geo/gazetteer-files.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|4.44|sqmi|sqkm|2}}, of which {{convert|4.06|sqmi|sqkm|2}} is land and {{convert|0.38|sqmi|sqkm|2}} is water.<ref name=\"Gazetteer files\">{{cite web|title=US Gazetteer files 2010 |url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=2012-11-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120702145235/http://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt |archivedate=2012-07-02 }}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1870= 590\n|1880= 671\n|1890= 1053\n|1900= 1387\n|1910= 1672\n|1920= 1754\n|1930= 2007\n|1940= 2219\n|1950= 2516\n|1960= 2951\n|1970= 3556\n|1980= 3670\n|1990= 4143\n|2000= 4843\n|2010= 5708\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=5923\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018CenPopScriptOnlyDirtyFixDoNotUse\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n[[Image:LakeMillsWisconsinSignWIS89.jpg|thumb|right|DOT sign]]\n[[Image:LakeMillsWisconsinDowntownWIS89.jpg|thumb|right|The west part of the town square on [[Wisconsin Highway 89|Highway 89]]]]\n\n===2010 census===\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name =\"wwwcensusgov\">{{cite web|title=U.S. Census website|url=https://www.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2012-11-18}}</ref> of 2010, there were 5,708 people, 2,319 households, and 1,503 families living in the city. The [[population density]] was {{convert|1405.9|PD/sqmi|PD/km2|1}}. There were 2,776 housing units at an average density of {{convert|683.7|/sqmi|/km2|1}}. The racial makeup of the city was 96.1% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 0.7% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.2% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 0.5% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 1.2% from [[Race (U.S. Census)|other races]], and 1.3% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 3.8% of the population.\n\nThere were 2,319 households of which 32.4% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 52.4% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 8.7% had a female householder with no husband present, 3.7% had a male householder with no wife present, and 35.2% were non-families. 28.2% of all households were made up of individuals and 11.6% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.42 and the average family size was 3.00.\n\nThe median age in the city was 37.2 years. 24.9% of residents were under the age of 18; 7% were between the ages of 18 and 24; 28.8% were from 25 to 44; 25.7% were from 45 to 64; and 13.5% were 65 years of age or older. The gender makeup of the city was 48.8% male and 51.2% female.\n\n===2000 census===\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=U.S. Census website}}</ref> of 2000, there were 4,843 people, 1,924 households, and 1,289 families living in the city. The [[population density]] was 1,415.6 people per square mile (546.8/km\u00b2). There were 2,065 housing units at an average density of 603.6 per square mile (233.1/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the city was 97.54% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 0.17% [[African American (U.S. Census)|Black]] or [[Race (United States Census)|African American]], 0.25% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 0.87% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.41% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 0.76% from two or more races. 2.33% of the population were [[Hispanic]] or [[Hispanic and Latino Americans|Latino]] of any race.\n\nThere were 1,924 households out of which 33.8% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 56.0% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 8.0% had a female householder with no husband present, and 33.0% were non-families. 26.8% of all households were made up of individuals and 13.0% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.49 and the average family size was 3.05.\n\nIn the city, the population was spread out with 27.2% under the age of 18, 6.6% from 18 to 24, 31.0% from 25 to 44, 20.8% from 45 to 64, and 14.5% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 36 years. For every 100 females, there were 92.9 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 91.1 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the city was $44,132, and the median income for a family was $54,131. Males had a median income of $36,394 versus $24,635 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $21,929. About 5.3% of families and 7.3% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 8.9% of those under age 18 and 6.1% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==Economy==\n*Seljan Company\n*Lewis Station Winery\n*Tyranena Brewing\n*Chapter 2 Inc.\n*J-MEC Equipment\n\n==Local Restaurants==\n*[[McDonald's]]\n*[[Culver's]]\n*[[Subway]]\n*Cafe on the Park\n*The Grist Bar and Table\n*[[Jimmy Johns]]\n*The Hub\n\n==Education==\nLake Mills is home to two school districts. The public school district, Lake Mills Area School District is the main district in the city and is home to the L-Cats. The other school district in the city is Lakeside Lutheran High School, a Lutheran high school with a smaller feeder school, St. Paul's school and church.<ref>https://www.llhs.org/</ref> Lakeside Lutheran is home to the Warriors. Both schools are members of the Capitol Conference of the [[WIAA]].<ref>https://www.lakemills.k12.wi.us/</ref>\n\n==Media==\nLake Mills is home to a weekly newspaper, [http://www.hngnews.com/lake_mills_leader/ The Lake Mills Leader].\nLake Mills is also home to What We Once Had, a local pop punk band that regularly performs shows around the Madison area.<ref>https://www.facebook.com/events/bos-mead-hall/what-we-once-had/498741544309485/</ref>\nLake Mills is also home to two band members of 2018-2019 Rockconsin Champions, Quick and Painless.<ref>http://www.quickandpainlessband.com/</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n{{div col}}\n*[[Mel J. Cyrak]], Wisconsin State Representative\n*[[Palmer F. Daugs]], Wisconsin State Representative\n*[[Ernst F. Detterer]], artist\n*[[George Papadopoulos]], former Trump campaign official and convicted felon\n*[[Nelson H. Falk]], Wisconsin State Representative\n*[[William Everson (Wisconsin)|William Everson]], Wisconsin State Representative\n*[[Charles Greenwood (Wisconsin)|Charles Greenwood]], Wisconsin State Representative\n*[[Carleton Bruns Joeckel]], librarian, author, and advocate for public libraries\n*[[Theodore S. Jones]], Wisconsin State Representative\n*[[Ron Swanson]], Pawnee Parks and Recreation Director\n*[[Laura L. Kiessling]], chemist\n*[[Louis Wescott Myers]], Chief Justice of the [[California Supreme Court]]\n*[[Charles Phillips (Wisconsin)|Charles Phillips]], Wisconsin State Representative\n*[[Hal Raether]], [[Major League Baseball|MLB]] pitcher\n*[[Jim Wilson (Oklahoma politician)|Jim Wilson]], Oklahoma state senator\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|1}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ci.lake-mills.wi.us/ City of Lake Mills]\n* [http://legendarylakemills.com/ Lake Mills Main Street Program]\n* [http://www.lakemills.org/ Lake Mills Area Chamber of Commerce]\n* Sanborn fire insurance maps:  [http://content.wisconsinhistory.org/cdm/ref/collection/maps/id/6654 1892] [http://content.wisconsinhistory.org/cdm/ref/collection/maps/id/6656 1898] [http://content.wisconsinhistory.org/cdm/ref/collection/maps/id/6660 1903] [http://content.wisconsinhistory.org/cdm/ref/collection/maps/id/6665 1912]\n\n{{Geographic Location (8-way)\n| North  = [[Waterloo, Wisconsin|Waterloo]]\n| West   = [[Deerfield, Wisconsin|Deerfield]]\n| Center = Lake Mills\n| East   = [[Johnson Creek, Wisconsin|Johnson Creek]]\n| South  = [[Cambridge, Wisconsin|Cambridge]]\n| image  = \n}}\n\n{{Jefferson County, Wisconsin}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Cities in Jefferson County, Wisconsin]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Lake Mills, Wisconsin\n|settlement_type          = [[City]]\n|nickname                 = \n|motto                    = \n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline            = Bandshelter.jpg\n|image_caption = Franklin Else Bandstand in Commons Park\n|imagesize                = \n|image_flag               = \n|image_seal               = \n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|pushpin_map              = USA Wisconsin\n|pushpin_mapsize          = 250px\n|pushpin_map_caption      = Location of Lake Mills within Wisconsin\n\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = {{flag|United States}}\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = {{flag|Wisconsin}}\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Wisconsin|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Jefferson County, Wisconsin|Jefferson]]\n\n<!-- Government -->\n|government_footnotes     = \n|government_type          = City Council\n|leader_title             = \n|leader_name              = \n|leader_title1            = \n|leader_name1             = \n|established_title        = \n|established_date         = \n\n<!-- Area -->\n|unit_pref                = Imperial\n|area_footnotes           = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web|title=2018 U.S. Gazetteer Files|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2018_Gazetteer/2018_gaz_place_55.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=Feb 15, 2020}}</ref>\n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_total_km2           = 11.53\n|area_land_km2            = 10.72\n|area_water_km2           = 0.81\n|area_total_sq_mi         = 4.45\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 4.14\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 0.31\n\n<!-- Population -->\n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_est           = 5923\n|pop_est_as_of            = 2018\n|population_footnotes     = <ref name =\"wwwcensusgov\"/>\n|population_total         = 5708\n|population_density_km2   = 552.35\n|population_density_sq_mi = 1430.68\n\n<!-- General information -->\n|timezone                 = [[North American Central Time Zone|Central (CST)]]\n|utc_offset               = -6\n|timezone_DST             = CDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -5\n|elevation_footnotes      = \n|elevation_m              = \n|elevation_ft             = \n|coordinates              = {{coord|43|4|48|N|88|54|33|W|region:US_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type         = [[Zip Code]]\n|postal_code              = 53551\n|area_code                = [[Area code 920|920]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standards|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 55-41675\n|blank1_name              = \n|blank1_info              = \n|website                  = {{URL|www.ci.lake-mills.wi.us}}\n|footnotes                = \n|pop_est_footnotes = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018CenPopScriptOnlyDirtyFixDoNotUse\"/>\n|image_map = File:Jefferson County Wisconsin Incorporated and Unincorporated areas Lake Mills Highlighted.svg\n|map_caption = Location of Lake Mills in Jefferson County, Wisconsin.\n}}\n\n'''Lake Mills''' is a city in [[Jefferson County, Wisconsin|Jefferson County]], [[Wisconsin]], United States. The population was 5,708 at the 2010 census.<ref name=\"Census 2010\">{{Cite web| url=https://www.census.gov| title=Profile of General Population and Housing Characteristics: 2010 Demographic Profile Data (DP-1): Lake Mills city, Wisconsin| publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]| accessdate=October 4, 2012}}</ref> The city is located partially within the [[Lake Mills (town), Wisconsin|Town of Lake Mills]].\n\n==History==\nLake Mills occupies the east shore of Rock Lake. The area was first settled by Captain Joseph Keyes. He called it \"Lake Mills\", after a [[saw mill]] and [[grist mill]] operating using power from nearby [[Rock Lake (Wisconsin)|Rock Lake]].<ref>{{cite book | url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_9V1IAAAAMAAJ | title=The Origin of Certain Place Names in the United States | publisher=[[United States Government Publishing Office|Government Printing Office]] | author=Gannett, Henry | year=1905 | pages=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_9V1IAAAAMAAJ/page/n178 179]}}</ref><ref>\"[http://www.wisconsinhistory.org/dictionary/index.asp?action=view&term_id=3463 Lake Mills &#91;origin of place name&#93;]\". ''Dictionary of Wisconsin History''.</ref>\n\nLake Mills was chartered in 1836, and the first building was built in 1837. The village of Lake Mills incorporated in 1852 out of the surrounding [[Lake Mills (town), Wisconsin|town of Lake Mills]]. In 1866 the village changed its name to \"Tyrahnena\", but changed it back again to \"Lake Mills\" the next year.<ref>\"An Act to consolidate and amend an act entitled 'an act to incorporate the village of Lake Mills,' and the several acts amendatory thereof, and to change the name of the village of Lake Mills to the village of Tyrahnena.\" in ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=lvbRAAAAMAAJ&lpg=PA378&ots=lm_PjpRuFx Private and Local Laws Passed by the Legislature of Wisconsin in the Year 1866]'', Chapter 188. April 13, 1866.</ref><ref>William J. Anderson and William A. Anderson (eds.). ''[http://digicoll.library.wisc.edu/cgi-bin/WI/WI-idx?type=goto&id=WI.WIBlueBk1929&page=629&isize=L The Wisconsin Blue Book 1929]''. Madison: Democrat Printing Co., 1929, p. 629.</ref> (''Tyrahnena'', or ''Tyranena'', is supposedly an indigenous name meaning \"sparkling waters\".)<ref>Lake Mills Chamber of Commerce. \"[http://www.vandregraphicdesign.com/vandreportshort/images/LM_Chamberbrochurefinal1.24.05std.pdf Legendary Lake Mills] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081013162008/http://www.vandregraphicdesign.com/vandreportshort/images/LM_Chamberbrochurefinal1.24.05std.pdf |date=2008-10-13 }}\".</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nLake Mills is located at {{coord|43|4|48|N|88|54|33|W|region:US_type:city}} (43.080108, -88.909209).<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geographies/reference-files/time-series/geo/gazetteer-files.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|4.44|sqmi|sqkm|2}}, of which {{convert|4.06|sqmi|sqkm|2}} is land and {{convert|0.38|sqmi|sqkm|2}} is water.<ref name=\"Gazetteer files\">{{cite web|title=US Gazetteer files 2010 |url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=2012-11-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120702145235/http://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt |archivedate=2012-07-02 }}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1870= 590\n|1880= 671\n|1890= 1053\n|1900= 1387\n|1910= 1672\n|1920= 1754\n|1930= 2007\n|1940= 2219\n|1950= 2516\n|1960= 2951\n|1970= 3556\n|1980= 3670\n|1990= 4143\n|2000= 4843\n|2010= 5708\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=5923\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018CenPopScriptOnlyDirtyFixDoNotUse\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n[[Image:LakeMillsWisconsinSignWIS89.jpg|thumb|right|DOT sign]]\n[[Image:LakeMillsWisconsinDowntownWIS89.jpg|thumb|right|The west part of the town square on [[Wisconsin Highway 89|Highway 89]]]]\n\n===2010 census===\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name =\"wwwcensusgov\">{{cite web|title=U.S. Census website|url=https://www.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2012-11-18}}</ref> of 2010, there were 5,708 people, 2,319 households, and 1,503 families living in the city. The [[population density]] was {{convert|1405.9|PD/sqmi|PD/km2|1}}. There were 2,776 housing units at an average density of {{convert|683.7|/sqmi|/km2|1}}. The racial makeup of the city was 96.1% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 0.7% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.2% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 0.5% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 1.2% from [[Race (U.S. Census)|other races]], and 1.3% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 3.8% of the population.\n\nThere were 2,319 households of which 32.4% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 52.4% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 8.7% had a female householder with no husband present, 3.7% had a male householder with no wife present, and 35.2% were non-families. 28.2% of all households were made up of individuals and 11.6% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.42 and the average family size was 3.00.\n\nThe median age in the city was 37.2 years. 24.9% of residents were under the age of 18; 7% were between the ages of 18 and 24; 28.8% were from 25 to 44; 25.7% were from 45 to 64; and 13.5% were 65 years of age or older. The gender makeup of the city was 48.8% male and 51.2% female.\n\n===2000 census===\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=U.S. Census website}}</ref> of 2000, there were 4,843 people, 1,924 households, and 1,289 families living in the city. The [[population density]] was 1,415.6 people per square mile (546.8/km\u00b2). There were 2,065 housing units at an average density of 603.6 per square mile (233.1/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the city was 97.54% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 0.17% [[African American (U.S. Census)|Black]] or [[Race (United States Census)|African American]], 0.25% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 0.87% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.41% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 0.76% from two or more races. 2.33% of the population were [[Hispanic]] or [[Hispanic and Latino Americans|Latino]] of any race.\n\nThere were 1,924 households out of which 33.8% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 56.0% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 8.0% had a female householder with no husband present, and 33.0% were non-families. 26.8% of all households were made up of individuals and 13.0% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.49 and the average family size was 3.05.\n\nIn the city, the population was spread out with 27.2% under the age of 18, 6.6% from 18 to 24, 31.0% from 25 to 44, 20.8% from 45 to 64, and 14.5% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 36 years. For every 100 females, there were 92.9 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 91.1 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the city was $44,132, and the median income for a family was $54,131. Males had a median income of $36,394 versus $24,635 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $21,929. About 5.3% of families and 7.3% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 8.9% of those under age 18 and 6.1% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==Economy==\n*Seljan Company\n*Lewis Station Winery\n*Tyranena Brewing\n*Chapter 2 Inc.\n*J-MEC Equipment\n\n==Local Restaurants==\n*[[McDonald's]]\n*[[Culver's]]\n*[[Subway]]\n*Cafe on the Park\n*The Grist Bar and Table\n*[[Jimmy Johns]]\n*The Hub\n\n==Education==\nLake Mills is home to two school districts. The public school district, Lake Mills Area School District is the main district in the city and is home to the L-Cats. The other school district in the city is Lakeside Lutheran High School, a Lutheran high school with a smaller feeder school, St. Paul's school and church.<ref>https://www.llhs.org/</ref> Lakeside Lutheran is home to the Warriors. Both schools are members of the Capitol Conference of the [[WIAA]].<ref>https://www.lakemills.k12.wi.us/</ref>\n\n==Media==\nLake Mills is home to a weekly newspaper, [http://www.hngnews.com/lake_mills_leader/ The Lake Mills Leader].\nLake Mills is also home to What We Once Had, a local pop punk band that regularly performs shows around the Madison area.<ref>https://www.facebook.com/events/bos-mead-hall/what-we-once-had/498741544309485/</ref>\nLake Mills is also home to two band members of 2018-2019 Rockconsin Champions, Quick and Painless.<ref>http://www.quickandpainlessband.com/</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n{{div col}}\n*[[Mel J. Cyrak]], Wisconsin State Representative\n*[[Palmer F. Daugs]], Wisconsin State Representative\n*[[Ernst F. Detterer]], artist\n*[[Nelson H. Falk]], Wisconsin State Representative\n*[[William Everson (Wisconsin)|William Everson]], Wisconsin State Representative\n*[[Charles Greenwood (Wisconsin)|Charles Greenwood]], Wisconsin State Representative\n*[[Carleton Bruns Joeckel]], librarian, author, and advocate for public libraries\n*[[Theodore S. Jones]], Wisconsin State Representative\n*[[Ron Swanson]], Pawnee Parks and Recreation Director\n*[[Laura L. Kiessling]], chemist\n*[[Louis Wescott Myers]], Chief Justice of the [[California Supreme Court]]\n*[[Charles Phillips (Wisconsin)|Charles Phillips]], Wisconsin State Representative\n*[[Hal Raether]], [[Major League Baseball|MLB]] pitcher\n*[[Jim Wilson (Oklahoma politician)|Jim Wilson]], Oklahoma state senator\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|1}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ci.lake-mills.wi.us/ City of Lake Mills]\n* [http://legendarylakemills.com/ Lake Mills Main Street Program]\n* [http://www.lakemills.org/ Lake Mills Area Chamber of Commerce]\n* Sanborn fire insurance maps:  [http://content.wisconsinhistory.org/cdm/ref/collection/maps/id/6654 1892] [http://content.wisconsinhistory.org/cdm/ref/collection/maps/id/6656 1898] [http://content.wisconsinhistory.org/cdm/ref/collection/maps/id/6660 1903] [http://content.wisconsinhistory.org/cdm/ref/collection/maps/id/6665 1912]\n\n{{Geographic Location (8-way)\n| North  = [[Waterloo, Wisconsin|Waterloo]]\n| West   = [[Deerfield, Wisconsin|Deerfield]]\n| Center = Lake Mills\n| East   = [[Johnson Creek, Wisconsin|Johnson Creek]]\n| South  = [[Cambridge, Wisconsin|Cambridge]]\n| image  = \n}}\n\n{{Jefferson County, Wisconsin}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities in Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Cities in Jefferson County, Wisconsin]]\n", "name_user": "LukastheWisconsinite", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNotable people", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lake_Mills,_Wisconsin"}
{"title_page": "Hasle Formation", "text_new": "{{infobox rockunit\n| name = Hasle Formation\n| age = [[Pliensbachian|Late Pliensbachian]]<br>~{{fossil range|190}}\n| period = Pliensbachian\n| overlies = [[R\u00f8nne Formation]]\n| underlies = [[Sorthat Formation]]\n| thickness = {{convert|80|-|140|m|ft|abbr=on}}\n| lithology = [[Siltstone]], [[sandstone]]\n| region = [[Bornholm]]\n| country = {{DNK}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Hasle Formation''' is a [[geologic formation]] on the island on [[Bornholm]], [[Denmark]]. It is of early to late [[Pliensbachian]] age. Vertebrate fossils have been uncovered from this formation.<ref name=rees>{{cite journal|last=Rees|first=J.|title=Early Jurassic selachians from the Hasle Formation on Bornholm, Denmark|journal=Acta Palaeontologica Polonica|year=1998|series=43|issue=3|pages=43\u2013439|url=http://www.app.pan.pl/archive/published/app43/app43-439.pdf}}</ref><ref name=finn>{{cite journal|authors=Donovan, Desmond T. & Surlyk, Finn|title=Lower Jurassic (Pliensbachian) ammonites from Bornholm, Baltic Sea, Denmark|journal=Geological Survey of Denmark and Greenland Bulletin|series=1|pages=555\u2013583|url=http://www.geus.dk/publications/bull/nr1_p555-583.pdf}}</ref>\n\n==Vertebrates==\n\n===Fish===\nUnidentified fin spines are known from this formation.<ref name=rees/>\n\n{{paleobiota-key-compact}}\n{|class =\"wikitable\" align=\"center\" width=\"100%\"\n|-\n! Genus\n! Species\n! Material\n! Notes\n! Images\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |\n''[[Hybodus]]''<ref name=rees/>\n|\n''H. reticulatus''<ref name=rees/>\n|\nunknown\n|\n| rowspan=\"2\" |\n[[File:Hybodus NT.jpg|thumb|200px|Restoration of ''Hybodus'']]\n|-\n|\n''H. delabechei''<ref name=rees/>\n|\nunknown\n|\n|-\n|\n''[[Lissodus]]''\n|\n''L. hasleensis'' sp. n.<ref name=rees/>\n|\nunknown\n|\n|\n|-\n|\n''[[Synechodus]]''<ref name=rees/>\n|\n''S. occultidens''<ref name=rees/>\n|\nunknown\n|\n|\n|-\n|\n''[[Paraorthacodus]]''<ref name=rees/>\n|\n''P. sp''<ref name=rees/>\n|\nunknown\n|\n|\n|-\n|\n''[[Agaleus]]''<ref name=rees/>\n|\n''A. dorsetensis''<ref name=rees/>\n|\nunknown\n|\n|\n|-\n|\n''[[Oblidens]]''<ref>{{Cite journal|author1=Christopher J. Duffin |author2=Jesper Mil\u00e0n |year=2017 |title=A new myriacanthid holocephalian from the Early Jurassic of Denmark |journal=Bulletin of the Geological Society of Denmark |volume=65 |pages=161\u2013170 |url=http://2dgf.dk/xpdf/bull65-161-170.pdf }}</ref>\n|\n''O. bornholmensis''<ref name=rees/>\n|\nUpper posterior (palatine) and lower posterior (mandibular)\ntooth plates.\n|\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n\n\n===Reptiles===\n\n====Theropoda====\n{|class =\"wikitable\" align=\"center\" width=\"100%\"\n|-\n! Genus\n! Species\n! Material\n! Notes\n! Images\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |\n[[Neotheropoda]]<ref name=jesper>Jesper Mil\u00e0n, Finn Surlyk. 2014: An enigmatic, diminutive theropod footprint in the shallow marine Pliensbachian Hasle Formation, Bornholm, Denmark</ref>\n|\nIndeterminate\n|\n|\n25 mm footprints referred to a non-avian Theropod.<ref name=jesper/>\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n====Sauropodomorpha====\n{|class =\"wikitable\" align=\"center\" width=\"100%\"\n|-\n! Genus\n! Species\n! Material\n! Notes\n! Images\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |\n[[Massospoda]]<ref> Mil\u00e0n, J., Cuny, G. (2019):Knogle fra mini sauropod fundet ved Hasle. Geomuseum Faxe Danmark. University of Lyon Frankrig. https://www.researchgate.net/publication/332291953_Knogle_fra_mini_sauropod_fundet_ved_Hasle</ref>\n|\nMassopoda Indeterminate\n|\n|\nDK966, a upper part of a femur from a juvenile animal\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n==Ammonites==\n\n{{paleobiota-key-compact}}\n{|class =\"wikitable\" align=\"center\" width=\"100%\"\n|-\n! Genus\n! Species\n! Material\n! Notes\n! Images\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" |\n''[[Aegoceras]]''<ref name=finn/>\n|\n''A. centaurus''<ref name=finn/>\n|\nspecimens<ref name=finn/>\n|\nLater renamed ''[[Beaniceras]] centaurus'', senior synonym of ''Aegoceras centaurus''<ref name=finn/>\n|\n|-\n|\n''A. armatum''<ref name=finn/>\n|\nspecimens<ref name=finn/>\n|\n|\n|-\n|\n